<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM26110 - Company reconstructions: practical issues</h1>
<h3>Requests for approval or clearance</h3>
<p>There is no statutory provision or requirement for HMRC to approve the terms of transactions affecting plan shares.  Practitioners will often request such approval, and approval of draft communications to participants.  Scheme Advisers should not comment on whether a particular transaction falls within the scope of paragraph 86 and whether any new holding can be treated as plan shares in accordance with paragraph 87.  Companies and their advisers must form their own view on the applicability of those provisions and treat the ‘new’ securities accordingly.</p>
<p>It is helpful for ESSU to receive such documents, however, and Scheme Advisers should review them for consistency with the plan rules and any analysis of the SIP legislation provided by the company and its advisers.   ESSU does not comment on the application of the legislation to a particular transaction in advance, however.</p>
<h3>Plan shares exchanged for other securities</h3>
<p>A company reconstruction can involve the surrender of all shares of a particular class, including plan shares, and their replacement by new shares in the same or a different company.  This can be achieved in a number of ways and under UK company law or overseas law depending on the country of registration of both the company whose shares are being replaced and of any acquiring company.</p>
<p>For example, in the UK, there can be</p>
<ul>
<li>a scheme of arrangement under section 899 Companies Act 2006</li>
<li>a general offer to existing shareholders to acquire all their shares or all shares of a particular class which will give the offeror control of the company</li>
<li>an internal re-organisation whereby shareholders are invited to approve a share-for-share exchange</li>
<li>a demerger whereby shareholders are invited to approve the exchange of their existing ordinary shares for a new denomination of ordinary shares plus shares in the newly-created company which is to be demerged</li>
</ul>
<p>Regardless of whether participants are invited by the trustees to accept an offer for their plan shares, if those shares are exchanged they are treated as withdrawn from the SIP.  Depending on the length of time that the plan shares have been in the SIP, this may result in a tax liability or, when partnership shares are withdrawn, the forfeiture of linked matching shares.</p>
